      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(logging): surface silent file-write failures and reject empty paths",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nWhen `logging.file` resolves to a path that cannot be written to (empty string, whitespace-only, directory, trailing slash, read-only filesystem, etc.), `appendLogLine` currently swallows the error and returns `false`. The caller drops the boolean return, so the gateway keeps running while no log lines are ever persisted. This is inconsistent with `rotateLogFile`, which at least emits one stderr warning on failure.\n\nThree small fixes:\n\n1. **Schema** (`src/config/zod-schema.ts:587`): `file: z.string().min(1).optional()` — rejects empty strings at config validation time.\n2. **resolveSettings** (`src/logging/logger.ts:559`): Trim whitespace and fall back to the default rolling path when the path is empty or whitespace-only — same behavior as when `logging.file` is unset.\n3. **Transport** (`src/logging/logger.ts:649-654`): Emit a one-time stderr warning (`[openclaw] log file write failed; continuing without file log ...`) on persistent write failure, mirroring the existing `rotateLogFile` failure path. The flag resets on the next successful write so fixing the path clears the warning.\n\n## Linked context\n\nN/A (no existing issue)\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n- **Behavior or issue addressed:** `logging.file` with empty/whitespace/read-only paths silently drops all log writes with zero user-visible feedback.\n- **Real environment tested:** Node 22.19, Linux x86_64, local checkout of `openclaw/openclaw` main (e84d68e794).\n- **Exact steps or command run after this patch:**\n  ```bash\n  node --import tsx /tmp/verify-logging-fix.mjs\n  ```\n  Script imports the patched `logger.ts` and verifies: empty path fallback, whitespace trimming, and stderr warning emission.\n- **Evidence after fix:** Terminal capture of `node` runtime verification (copied live output):\n\n  ```\n  === Test 1: empty logging.file ===\n\n    Input: file=\"\"\n    Resolved file: /tmp/openclaw/openclaw-2026-06-17.log\n    PASS\n\n  === Test 2: whitespace-only logging.file ===\n\n    Input: file=\"   \"\n    Resolved file: /tmp/openclaw/openclaw-2026-06-17.log\n    PASS\n\n  === Test 3: trailing whitespace trimming ===\n\n    Input: file=\"/tmp/test-openclaw.log  \"\n    Resolved file: /tmp/test-openclaw.log\n    PASS\n\n  === Test 4: stderr warning on write failure ===\n\n  [openclaw] log file write failed; continuing without file log file=/tmp/openclaw-log-fail-proof-1ab1fbc7-2810-405e-bed0-5ad7665a618b/openclaw.log (will retry silently; check path/permissions)\n    stderr warning: [openclaw] log file write failed; continuing without file log file=...\n    PASS\n\n  === ALL PASSED ===\n  ```\n\n- **Observed result after fix:** Empty/whitespace paths now fall back to the default rolling log path (instead of passing `\"\"` to `fs.appendFileSync`). Write failures now emit a one-time stderr warning, matching the `rotateLogFile` behavior.\n- **What was not tested:** End-to-end test with a real read-only container filesystem (covered by the chmod-based write-failure test).\n\n## Tests and validation\n\n```\n$ pnpm test src/logging/log-file-silent-failure.test.ts src/config/logging-file-empty.test.ts src/logging/log-file-size-cap.test.ts\n✓ Test Files  3 passed (3)\n✓ Tests      10 passed (10)\n```\n\n## Risk checklist\n\n- [x] Does this change affect user-visible behavior? **Yes** — users who previously had empty or whitespace-only `logging.file` will now get the default rolling log path instead of silent write failures; unwritable paths now produce a one-time stderr warning.\n- [x] Does this change affect configuration? **Yes** — empty string for `logging.file` is now rejected by schema validation (`min(1)`). This is backwards-compatible: empty paths previously produced silent failures; they now produce a clear validation error.\n- [x] Does this change affect security? **No**\n- [x] Does this change affect plugins or providers? **No**\n- [x] Does this change affect docs? **No**\n- [x] Is this change backwards-compatible? **Yes** — all previously-valid non-empty paths continue to work identically. Empty paths that previously silently failed now either fail validation or fall back to default.\n",
        "branch": "fix/logging-silent-file-write-failure",
